{[BID 1H]
South opens, and with an opening hand and a five-card major the start is clear.
@S @v(open|opens) the longer major to describe the hand in one bid: 1\H shows five or more hearts and a real opening.
[BID 2N]
Holding four-card support and the values for game, @S @v(have|has) far too much for a simple raise.
2NT here is Jacoby — a game-forcing major raise that asks @your partner to describe shape and strength below game.
[BID 3C]
With a useful singleton, @S @v(show|shows) it: over Jacoby 2NT, three of a new suit names a singleton or void in that suit.
That shortness is exactly what @your partner wants to hear when judging slam.
[BID 4D]
Knowing the trump fit and the shortness, @S @v(start|starts) describing controls.
4\D is a cue-bid, showing first-round control of diamonds and accepting partner's interest in a bigger contract.
[BID 4N]
With the partnership clearly headed past game, @S @v(take|takes) charge.
4NT is Roman Key Card Blackwood, asking @your partner to count the key cards for the agreed trump suit.
[BID 5C]
Answering the ask, @S @v(show|shows) @your key-card count up the line.
The step response tells partner exactly how many aces and the trump king are present.
[BID 5H]
With the key cards counted, @S @v(stop|stops) to let partner place the contract.
5\H confirms the partnership is not missing two key cards and leaves the final decision to @your partner.
[BID 6H]
Weighing the controls and shortness, @S @v(judge|judges) there is more than enough for slam.
6\H invites partner to go on if the values are truly at the top.
[BID 7H]
With every key card accounted for and a source of tricks, @S @v(bid|bids) the grand.
7\H commits to all thirteen, trusting the controls the auction has shown.
[show NS] A model Jacoby 2NT slam auction. North's opening strength and South's solid heart suit with a club singleton mesh perfectly; the cue-bid and key-card exchange confirm every control, and 7\H rolls home on the heart fit. When the shortness fits partner's losers and no key card is missing, the grand is simply there to be bid.}
